entry.title: iwa: Add localized Error for Isolated Web App Error Page
entry.content:
Adds special handling for some net::Error codes.



net::ERR_INVALID_WEB_BUNDLE: when the swbn file has been removed or no

longer valid.



net::ERR_CONNECTION_REFUSED: when dev-proxy server cannot be reached.



All other net::Error will be displayed as net::ERR_XXX.



HTTP status errors will have their net::Error set as

ERR_HTTP_RESPONSE_CODE_FAILURE, they will be directed to use default

error page at a higher level. This means for the moment,

MaybeGetIsolatedWebAppErrorPageInfo can not encounter

ERR_HTTP_RESPONSE_CODE_FAILURE. IWA will continue to use default error

page for HTTP status errors.

entry.title: [Extensions] Use browser context unique id in extension utils
entry.content:
Previously, extensions util generated a "unique id" given a browser

context and stored them in a `std::map`. This was problematic because if the BrowserContext gets

destroyed, another BrowserContext could be placed in the same address

and get the "unique id" of the destroyed BrowserContext.



Instead, we can use the BrowserContext::UniqueId that guarantees a

unique id. We maintain the map generated by extension utils because

the types are different (int vs string) and because it's also used by

the renderer.

entry.title: Reland: Specify overlay damage in pixels in viewport space
entry.content:
Changes since revert: none.



Original Description:



Currently we are doing a bunch of math to convert damage into buffer

space, and then we're undoing most of that math to convert back to

surface space before passing it to Wayland.



This doesn't really make sense because Exo doesn't even support the

buffer space damage API. It's also an opportunity for floating point

errors to occur. And the work is ultimately unnecessary because damage

in Ash is only useful in pixel pixel coordinates.



There are also some existing bugs in the math when dealing with solid

color overlays which don't really have a buffer space to begin with.

Fixing this bug will allow us to specify most damage on the root

surface, which is technically a solid color overlay.

entry.title: Reland "Allow utilities to preload libraries before sandbox lockdown"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit fe96e5d8bdf603c73616ff87082352a562de1be7



Now builds correctly for asan.



Additionally, during testing a flaky failure was uncovered where

the mojo service could start before the preloading happened, this

is resolved by moving the preloading code ahead of IO thread

creation in UtilityMain.



Original change's description:

> Allow utilities to preload libraries before sandbox lockdown

>

> Some utilities on Windows wrap dynamic libraries which might be

> distributed as components. Allowing these to load requires punching

> holes in the sandbox using file interceptions that are being phased

> out.

>

> This CL introduces a mechanism for service processes to specify a

> list of dll paths which will be loaded before the sandbox goes into

> lockdown. They can later be loaded by code using the same path, as

> Windows keeps them in memory.

>

> The mechanism uses a new opaque data transfer mechanism in the

> sandbox which will extend to different uses later. For

> now the list of DLLs is the only data transferred so this CL uses

> base::Pickle to serialize & transfer the DLLs to load.

>

> As loading arbitrary DLLs is a powerful capability a passkey is

> added for the new service process host option, and a file containing

> valid callers is added with OWNERS from the sandbox to ensure

> security review.

>

> A following CL will enable this behavior for screen_ai, but at this

> point only tests exercise these APIs

>

> The flow is roughly:

> ---

> In the browser/broker:-

>

> ServiceProcessHost gets a new option:

> .WithPreloadedLibraries

>

> UtilityProcessHost gets a new member:

> preload_libraries_

>

> UtilityProcessHost gives this to the UtilitySandboxedProcessLauncherDelegate

>

> UtilitySandboxedProcessLauncherDelegate turns a list of DLLs into an

> opaque blob and attaches it to the sandbox's TargetPolicy during

> PreSpawnTarget.

>

> The sandbox smuggles this blob into the target (previous CL).

>

> In the child/target:-

>

> The UtilityMain knows it might have a blob, so asks TargetServices.

>

> UtilityMain coordinates with its sandbox delegate, so knows that

> the blob is a pickled list of DLLs.

>

> UtilityMain loads these dlls before sandbox lockdown.

> ---

>

entry.title: [A11y] Small simplification to ignored computation for block flows
entry.content:
This continues the work from CL:4194697 to simplify our code that decides whether or not a block flow is ignored. By simplifying, we improve performance and predictability, and have fewer cases where we miss an invalidation when one of the dependent conditions changes.



In this case, we remove code that checks to see if a cursor can be set inside of the block flow. As a result, a few more harmless generic containers are introduced to the hierarchy. It is not necessary to remove all uninteresting generic containers, and it is only an optimization to do so. In this case, the extra "magic" regarding NGCursor is not worth having a few extra generic containers in the tree.



The code is now clearer and less likely to run into a state where there is a stale tree structure containing a node with the wrong ignored state, confusing the serializer.

entry.title: [fuchsia] Reject ContextProvider.Create() without a service directory

Require that the `params` passed to ContextProvider's Create() method

have `service_directory`. The presence of `service_directory` is

currently used by WebInstanceHost to decide where to obtain capabilities

for the new WebInstance.

also replaced the `CreateValidatesServiceDirectory` test with

svc" directory was offered or present in

offered from the test Component to the WebInstance via the

`!with_service_directory` path. This is exactly the case this CL is

intended to prevent. That test is replaced with a new

`CreateContextWithoutServiceDirectoryFails` test that is nearly

identical to the previous `CreateValidatesServiceDirectory` test.

ErrorReportOption::kReport is only used in 2 places:

javascript: url execution. HTMLFrameElementBase should use

LocalFrame::CanNavigate(), which is specifically designed for this

sort of navigation security check, and provides a much more precise

tests. It's not clear to me that this case is reachable. So it's

not clear we need to report anything.



With those two cases removed, we can get rid of the ErrorReportOption

enum entirely and simplify both the public interface and the internal

implementation of BindingSecurity.

entry.title: [EnumSet] Refactor constructor usages
entry.content:
TL;DR: EnumSet variadic template ctor is being replaced with ctor

accepting std::initializer_list. Some usages are not compatible and this

CL updates them.



Implicit EnumValue->EnumSet conversions and direct calls of variadic

template constructor (e.g. EnumSet(value1,...)) don't work with

initializer_list ctor. This CL replaces them with:

1. [Only variables initializations] EnumSet set = {value1, ...};

2. [Only inside macro invocations] EnumSet({value1, ...})

special case of implicit conversion, intentionally supported in STL

and by clang-tidy warnings):

foo(value1) -> foo({value1});

foo(EnumSet(value1, ...)) -> foo({value1, ...});

4. EnumSet(value1, ...) -> EnumSet{value1, ...};



Note that 3 and 4 are mostly the same, in most places I made a choice

that resembles pre-existing code closer (exceptions are mostly usages of

Sync EnumSets).



Motivation:

EnumSet variadic template constructor is defective in a sense that it

allows code like this to compile:

explicit will disallow nice STL-like usage:

class C {

using std::initializer_list, this refactoring does the same for EnumSet.

entry.title: Don't close dialogs in response to cancel event
entry.content:
A *trusted* cancel event can close dialog elements. This is hooked up to

the default keyboard event handler, which fires a trusted cancel event,

in order to make the escape key close dialog elements. When the cancel

event has preventDefault called on it, it prevents the dialog element

from being closed because the dialog's DefaultEventHandler won't be

called anymore.



This caused an issue where a new trusted cancel event started being

emitted by file input elements, which unexpectedly caused the dialog to

be closed.



This patch replaces the dialog's DefaultEventHandler with a check to see

if the event was defaultPrevented where it gets emitted in the keyboard

event handler.
